e documentation in two communities with high migration rates -- t12. Linguistic ideologies as a crucial factor in language revitalization: A look at the Mayangna languages of Nicaragua -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUp to now, the focus in the field of language documentation has been predominantly on North American and Australian languages. However, the greatest genetic diversity in languages is found in Latin America, home to over 100 distinct language families. This book gives the Latin American context the attention it requires by consolidating the work of field researchers experienced in the region into one volume for the first time.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEndangered languageszLatin America. 0aLanguage revivalzLatin America. 0aLinguistic minoritieszLatin America. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLanguage Documentation.  aLatin America.1 aAmaro, Karina Ivett Verdín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArias, Rocío Rojas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalna, Mayangna Yulbarangyang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedicto, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBáez, Gabriela Pérez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Tutupika Carillo de la, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalucio, Ana Vilacy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, Saul Santos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuadarrama, Octavio Alonso González, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re